[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:AQ832.52.KJ6.Q83 KT54.AJ7.T92.A54 7.QT9643.Q75.K62 J96.K8.A843.JT97"]
[Scoring ""]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "2H"]
[Result ""]
{<b>Bidding.</b> After North's 1\S opening, South isn't strong enough to bid
2\H directly.  So South starts with the forcing 1NT.  North bids 2\C, which may
be short.  South can now rebid 2\H, showing 6+ hearts and 6-10 points.  This is
a "drop" bid, which partner should normally pass.

<b>Opening Lead.</b>  \CJ, top of a solid sequence.  If dummy plays low, East
should encourage with the \C5, saving the \CA to capture dummy's queen later.

<b>Declarer's plan.</b>  Declarer has 2 club losers, 1 diamond loser, and 2 or
3 heart losers.  There's no way to avoid losing the top two trumps, but playing
East for the \HJ gives declarer the chance to make the contract.

So declarer should win the first club with the \CK, lead a spade to dummy's
ace, and lead a low heart back.  If East plays low, South should insert the
ten.


These hands are from <i><span style=color:#00f>2 Over 1 Game Force</span></i>,
by Audrey Grant and Eric Rodwell.  This is a great book for people who play the
2 Over 1 bidding system.


}
[BCFlags "1f"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 1NT =1= Pass
2C =2= Pass 2H =3= AP
[Note "1:Forcing (one round)"]
[Note "2:May be as few as 2 or 3"]
[Note "3:6+ hearts and 6-10 points"]
[Play "W"]
CJ

[Event "Forcing 1NT"]
[Site "-"]
[Date "2022.12.18"]
[Board "2"]
[West ""]
[North ""]
[East ""]
[South ""]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "E:AQ852.A9.52.AK92 JT7643.53.KJ64.3 K.K764.AT73.J765 9.QJT82.Q98.QT84"]
[Scoring ""]
[Declarer "W"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
{<b>Bidding.</b> With a semi-balanced 17 HCP, and a 5 card major, it's usually
best to open the major.  West makes the forcing 1NT bid, show 6-12 points. 
Opener rebids 2\C, which could be short.  West now rebids 2NT, showing 11-12
HCP and a balanced hand.  The singleton \SK is okay here because this was
partner's opening suit.  With a maximum opener, East continues to game.

<b>Opening Lead.</b>  Top of a solid sequence.

<b>Declarer's plan.</b>  Declarer has 8 top tricks, and needs to develop one
more.  The club suit is the most likely candidate.  Since declarer just need 1
extra trick in clubs, it's safest to lead a club to dummy's king, then lead low
back to the \CJ.  When we see South discarding on the 2nd round, we will lose
that trick, but can take the marked finesse through North for the remaining two
club tricks. 
}
[BCFlags "1f"]
[Auction "E"]
1S Pass 1NT =1= Pass
2C =2= Pass 2NT =3= Pass
3NT AP
[BCNote ""]
[Note "1:Forcing one round"]
[Note "2:May be as short as 2 or 3"]
[Note "3:11-12 balanced"]
[Play "N"]
HQ

[Event "Forcing 1NT"]
[Site "-"]
[Date "2022.12.18"]
[Board "3"]
[West ""]
[North ""]
[East ""]
[South ""]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "S:AJ642.62.Q72.KQT 95.A85.JT984.A74 KQ8.Q743.A65.963 T73.KJT9.K3.J852"]
[Scoring ""]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "3S"]
[Result ""]
{<b>Bidding.</b>  South has 12 HCP and one length point, for a total of 13, and
opens 1\S.  North has 3-card support, and 11 points, and wants to show that. 
This is a 3-card limit raise, and we have to make two bids: start with the
forcing 1NT, then jump in spades on the 2nd round.  Opener is a minimum, so
passes 3\S.

<b>Opening Lead.</b>  Top of a solid sequence.

<b>Declarer's plan.</b>  Declarer has 5 trumps, and with the opening lead will
get 2 diamonds (by ducking trick one in dummy).  So declarer needs 2 tricks
from the club suit.  Best is to lead clubs twice to finesse.  This will have to
be done while drawing trumps, because trumps are dummy's only entry.  The first
time declarer should lead to the \CK.  If this loses to the ace, then the
second time declarer should lead to the \CT.

<b>Defense.</b>  West can give declarer a problem by smoothly declining to
capture the \CK with the \CA.  This will encourage declarer to lead to the \CQ
next, which will lose to the \CA, and set up partner's \CJ in the process.}
[BCFlags "1f"]
[Auction "S"]
1S Pass 1NT =1= Pass
2C =2= Pass 3S =3= AP
[Note "1:Forcing one round"]
[Note "2:May be as short as 2 or 3"]
[Note "3:3 spades and 11-12 points"]
[Play "W"]
DJ

[Event "Forcing 1NT"]
[Site "-"]
[Date "2022.12.18"]
[Board "4"]
[West ""]
[North ""]
[East ""]
[South ""]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:63.QJT86.K76.AK4 KJ8752.A53.J4.86 AQ9.94.Q9532.J93 T4.K72.AT8.QT752"]
[Scoring ""]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "1NT"]
[Result ""]
{<b>Bidding.</b>  West opens 1\H, and North overcalls 1\S.  East should respond
1NT, showing 6-10 points and a spade stopper.  This is not a Forcing 1NT,
because RHO made an interfering bid.

<b>Opening Lead.</b>  With a doubleton in partner's suit, lead the higher of
the two cards.

<b>Declarer's plan.</b>  Declarer has two spades, and two clubs, and needs to
get three more tricks from hearts.  But the defenders will get the lead twice
while establishing the hearts, and there's a risk they can set up their spades
in the process.

To make things more difficult for them, duck the first spade.  South can lead
spades a second time, and declarer wins.  Now lead a heart, and south doesn't
have any more spades to lead when getting in with the \HK.  This will let
declarer come home with 2 spades, 3 hearts, and 2 clubs - 7 in all.

Note: If declarer doesn't duck the first spade, the contract will be down
several tricks.
}
[BCFlags "1f"]
[Auction "W"]
1H 1S 1NT =1= AP
[BCNote ""]
[Note "1:Standard 6-10 NT here, not forcing, since RHO made a bid."]
[Play "S"]
ST
